Want to expand on the topic a bit. We’ve been debating whether to include a base AL/ML model with the code. It may give everyone a quick start but also pigeonhole ingenuity.

The general concept is to gather a bunch of parameters including technical, fundamental, macroeconomical, sentimental, and feed them to a model that makes predictions. The classic SVM has worked well and still works to this day, despite all the hype since ChatGPT came to the scene. Transformers have been a mixed bag but talented miners may find better use out of them.

The essential part is still “feature engineering” in machine learning, i.e. pick the relevant parameters that capture market conditions. Grid search and backtesting are the bread-n-butter in optimizing parameters and weights as usual. Optimize based on Kelly, covariance, and score. Our unique score formula is top notch in surfacing performant strategies. Ensemble or composite strategies beat isolated ones hands down. The basics are still the most important: moving average and crossover, support and resistance, multiple timeframes i.e. long timeframe for direction and short timeframe for execution.

This is barely scratching the surface based on our own experience. Predicting the future in a seemingly random environment is the hardest problem to solve, and that’s why we’re here, working with the Bittensor community to make magic and miracles happen. There's no doubt it can happen, as RenTech and others have shown the way.
